election_record.label: New Jersey 1824 Electoral College

overview.note: John W. Scott, John Beatty, Jr., Abraham Brown and Ephraim Miller had been announced candidates but declined or withdrew before the election. The votes for John W. Scott and John Beatty, Jr. came at the expense of their replacements, James Cook and Jacob Kline. The votes for Abraham Brown and Ephraim Miller came at the expense of their replacements, Philip T. Howell and Jacob Glover.
John Buck, Isaac Q. Farlee, Joseph Kille, James Cook and Jacob Kline were also voted for by the supporters of William Crawford.

sub_unit.name: Northampton
sub_unit.note: The New-Jersey Mirror and Burlington County Advertiser (Mount Holly, NJ) lists 122 votes for Joseph Kille.

sub_unit.name: Essex
sub_unit.note: The True American November 27, 1824 lists 1417 votes for Isaac G. Farlee, 1172 votes for James Parker, 1172 votes for Peter Wilson, 1172 votes for Daniel Vliet, 1734 votes for John M. Sherred, 1736 votes for James T. Dunn, 1733 votes for Jacob Glover, 1733 votes for David Dubois, 1728 votes for Jesse Upson and 319 votes for Peter B. Shaffer.

sub_unit.name: Acquackanonk
sub_unit.note: 48 votes for Joseph Glover from the town of Aquackanonk, Essex County, were not reported in the Official Canvass.

sub_unit.name: Greenwich
sub_unit.note: Peter Wilson received 8 votes as Doctor Pete Wilson.

sub_unit.name: Woolwich
sub_unit.note: Peter Wilson received 23 votes as Doctor Pete Wilson.

sub_unit.name: Sussex
sub_unit.note: In Sussex County, on the Original Election Returns, John Beatty was listed as John Beatty, Jr.

sub_unit.name: Mansfield
sub_unit.note: 51 votes for John Dodd from the town of Mansfield in Sussex county were not reported in the Official Canvass.
